00:58:36.840 --> 00:58:38.880
it says likely to be

00:58:38.880 --> 00:58:41.810
in the succeeding three-year
period adversely affected.

00:58:41.810 --> 00:58:44.810
And then, it doesn't
again say in their ability

00:58:44.810 --> 00:58:46.740
to make likely non-infringing uses.

00:58:46.740 --> 00:58:50.520
It says in their ability to
make non-infringing uses.

00:58:50.520 --> 00:58:55.410
And, you know, a judge doesn't tell
you this is likely what the law is.

00:58:55.410 --> 00:58:57.760
The judge says this
is what the law is.

00:58:57.760 --> 00:59:00.330
And I think that's the standard
that was called for here.

00:59:00.330 --> 00:59:02.780
The Office has taken
a different approach.

00:59:02.780 --> 00:59:06.970
But I don't think there's anything
for the proponents to criticize

00:59:06.970 --> 00:59:08.910
because the Office is
already interpreting it

00:59:08.910 --> 00:59:11.270
to say likely non-infringing.

00:59:11.270 --> 00:59:15.780
To take it a whole step further and
say that the copyright owner needs

00:59:15.780 --> 00:59:19.630
to come in and show that there
is an adverse judicial precedent

00:59:19.630 --> 00:59:23.550
against their position
in order to succeed

00:59:23.550 --> 00:59:28.050
in the rulemaking just
completely upends copyright law

00:59:28.050 --> 00:59:31.910
because the default in section 106
is that if you're making a copy,

00:59:31.910 --> 00:59:33.890
if you're adapting
a work, et cetera,

00:59:33.890 --> 00:59:35.370
you're committing an
act of infringement.

00:59:35.370 --> 00:59:39.600
You then have an affirmative burden
to prove a defense such as fair use

00:59:39.600 --> 00:59:41.310
or one of the other exceptions.

00:59:41.310 --> 00:59:46.520 position:56%
And so, I don't see why the standard
would differ in this context.

00:59:46.520 --> 00:59:48.410
That's all I needed to say.

