of discussion in the comments.

01:20:43.950 --> 01:20:48.920
And that's the statutory language
referring to such other factors

01:20:48.920 --> 01:20:53.970
as the librarian may wish
to consider and the role

01:20:53.970 --> 01:20:59.030
of non-copyright issues
as part of the rulemaking.

01:20:59.030 --> 01:21:03.150
You know, we heard from
several commenters arguing

01:21:03.150 --> 01:21:08.090
that the Copyright Office should
not properly consider these types

01:21:08.090 --> 01:21:10.870
of issues and should leave
them to other agencies.

01:21:10.870 --> 01:21:15.880 position:56%
I think-- and we also had some
discussion about sort of the process

01:21:15.880 --> 01:21:19.740
that that should involve,
whether it's within our authority

01:21:19.740 --> 01:21:23.390
to affirmatively reach out
to other agencies or whether

01:21:23.390 --> 01:21:30.450
under the statutory language we're
limited to consulting with NTIA.

01:21:30.450 --> 01:21:34.610
So we'd appreciate
your views on sort of--

01:21:34.610 --> 01:21:39.740
on the proper role of other
agencies and how we should go

01:21:39.740 --> 01:21:44.620
about consulting with them on
issues within their jurisdiction.

01:21:44.620 --> 01:21:45.920
Mr. Mohr?

01:21:45.920 --> 01:21:50.190
&gt;&gt; Chris Mohr: Again, I
would go back to the concept

01:21:50.190 --> 01:21:54.040
of the administrative
record and the breadth.

01:21:54.040 --> 01:21:57.080
And I think that so
long as the things

01:21:57.080 --> 01:22:00.150
on which you rely are
publicly disclosed,

01:22:00.150 --> 01:22:04.670
I think you have a
fair amount of leeway

01:22:04.670 --> 01:22:07.620
to amass information
from different sources.

01:22:07.620 --> 01:22:11.950
But when you issue the rule, you
have to explain, yes, we saw this

01:22:11.950 --> 01:22:14.770 position:56%
and I think there probably has to be
some opportunity for public comment

01:22:14.770 --> 01:22:16.450
on whatever was received.

01:22:16.450 --> 01:22:21.200
But outside of that, I think that
was exactly the right approach was

01:22:21.200 --> 01:22:24.970
to get information from
people who are experts

01:22:24.970 --> 01:22:28.740
in particular subject matter that
the Copyright Office is not and,

01:22:28.740 --> 01:22:30.360
you know, weigh their views,

01:22:30.360 --> 01:22:34.050
even if you didn't completely
agree with them all the time.

01:22:34.050 --> 01:22:36.730
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Mr. Panjwani?

01:22:36.730 --> 01:22:42.660
&gt;&gt; Raza Panjwani: It's been our
perspective that the other factors

01:22:42.660 --> 01:22:47.780
that the librarian shall consider
factor is directed at the fact

01:22:47.780 --> 01:22:52.020
that the proponents of an exemption
must prove something beyond

01:22:52.020 --> 01:22:54.950
copyright itself, which
would be non-infringement,

01:22:54.950 --> 01:22:58.940
in order to justify adverse effects
and that allows the librarian

01:22:58.940 --> 01:23:03.560
to consider additional harms
experienced by proponents

01:23:03.560 --> 01:23:05.610
in determining whether or not
an exemption is warranted.

01:23:05.610 --> 01:23:09.610
In the last proceeding, we had of
course this interagency process

01:23:09.610 --> 01:23:11.670
and it's consideration
of many other factors,

01:23:11.670 --> 01:23:16.590
and it's been our perspective
that this is not really necessary

01:23:16.590 --> 01:23:19.510
in the process of determining
whether an exemption is warranted.

01:23:19.510 --> 01:23:22.950
This is a question of whether
copyright liability will attach

01:23:22.950 --> 01:23:24.860
for certain activity.

01:23:24.860 --> 01:23:28.610
And I don't think that, you know,

01:23:28.610 --> 01:23:31.180
the technological protection
measures were considered

01:23:31.180 --> 01:23:35.440
as a policy panacea for any
consideration under the sun,

01:23:35.440 --> 01:23:38.500
whether that be product safety,
whether that be emissions,

01:23:38.500 --> 01:23:41.230
whether that be medical devices.

01:23:41.230 --> 01:23:45.970
I think there's often a conflation
of, you know, there's software

01:23:45.970 --> 01:23:47.660
in here that implicates copyright.

01:23:47.660 --> 01:23:49.250
Therefore, there's
something different now,

01:23:49.250 --> 01:23:51.190
whereas a lot of these
devices have existed

01:23:51.190 --> 01:23:54.910
and these concerns have existed
in the mechanical, non-software,

01:23:54.910 --> 01:23:57.670
non-copyright-implicating way.

01:23:57.670 --> 01:24:01.590
And law and policy has developed to
address those issues historically.

01:24:01.590 --> 01:24:04.970
I think the car example is a
great one in which, you know,

01:24:04.970 --> 01:24:07.230
there's concerns about, will
people could modify the software

01:24:07.230 --> 01:24:10.070
on their car to allow them to
violate emissions standards.

01:24:10.070 --> 01:24:12.300
People have been modifying
their cars for a century,

01:24:12.300 --> 01:24:14.660 position:56%
for as long as there have been cars.

01:24:14.660 --> 01:24:16.560
And there have been
rules against that.

01:24:16.560 --> 01:24:19.410
We have annual inspections
of cars to check

01:24:19.410 --> 01:24:20.710
for emissions and things like that.

01:24:20.710 --> 01:24:24.030
I think most areas of law have
already responded to the concerns

01:24:24.030 --> 01:24:26.200
that we have brought up in a while.

01:24:26.200 --> 01:24:29.670
I admire the Copyright Office
for thinking afar and realizing

01:24:29.670 --> 01:24:33.310
that a lot of these things are
implicated by software now,

01:24:33.310 --> 01:24:35.850
I don't think that this
proceeding is the appropriate venue

01:24:35.850 --> 01:24:37.240
for addressing those concerns.

01:24:37.240 --> 01:24:40.280
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: So just to be
clear, taking the last rulemaking

01:24:40.280 --> 01:24:43.570
as an example, we got a
petition that referenced--

01:24:43.570 --> 01:24:45.690
I think this was sort of more
broadly to the internet of things

01:24:45.690 --> 01:24:49.970
and it wasn't a lot of specifics
as to what they wanted to do,

01:24:49.970 --> 01:24:53.280
but examples of I'd like
to hack the subway system,

01:24:53.280 --> 01:24:56.940
I'd like to hack the nuclear power
grid, I'd like to hack automobiles.

01:24:56.940 --> 01:25:00.590
I mean, should the Copyright
Office entirely ignore whether

01:25:00.590 --> 01:25:03.410
or not there is a potential
public safety concern?

01:25:03.410 --> 01:25:05.840
&gt;&gt; Raza Panjwani: I believe hackers
will hackers will hack those things

01:25:05.840 --> 01:25:07.580
if they are malicious,
regardless of whether

01:25:07.580 --> 01:25:10.000
or not there's a 1201
exemption for it.

01:25:10.000 --> 01:25:11.300
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Sure.

01:25:11.300 --> 01:25:14.470
Mr. Williams.

01:25:14.470 --> 01:25:15.770
&gt;&gt; Matt Williams: Thanks.

01:25:15.770 --> 01:25:20.480
I just quickly wanted to reiterate
what Allan Adler and Troy Dow said

01:25:20.480 --> 01:25:26.500
in the last panel, that you have
to be really, really careful

01:25:26.500 --> 01:25:31.020
about what constitutes a
core copyright concern.

01:25:31.020 --> 01:25:35.950
That term, it would have to
be very carefully defined

01:25:35.950 --> 01:25:45.070
to have any real benefit and
that there is this distinction,

01:25:45.070 --> 01:25:47.810
as Professor Tushnet articulated,

01:25:47.810 --> 01:25:50.030
between access controls
and copy controls.

01:25:50.030 --> 01:25:54.280
And it's clear that Congress did
intend to protect access controls

01:25:54.280 --> 01:25:57.430
for their own purpose
as access controls

01:25:57.430 --> 01:26:01.370
to prevent unauthorized access
to works that are available

01:26:01.370 --> 01:26:06.100
for subscription or
on-demand availability.

01:26:06.100 --> 01:26:10.870
And one fact pattern that I
think demonstrates the importance

01:26:10.870 --> 01:26:15.880
of that clearly is if you've
got a work that is available

01:26:15.880 --> 01:26:18.700
and it's protected by an access
control and it's also protected

01:26:18.700 --> 01:26:21.430
by a completely separate
copy control,

01:26:21.430 --> 01:26:24.840
if you were to hack the
access control and gain copy--

01:26:24.840 --> 01:26:27.580
and gain access to the copy,
you could watch the movie,

01:26:27.580 --> 01:26:29.860
you could listen to the song,
you could read the book.

01:26:29.860 --> 01:26:31.670
If the copy control
remained in place,

01:26:31.670 --> 01:26:36.460
theoretically there's no nexus
to even a possible infringement.

01:26:36.460 --> 01:26:38.380
And then, there would
be no violation.

01:26:38.380 --> 01:26:41.800
I think Congress clearly
intended to prohibit that conduct.

01:26:41.800 --> 01:26:44.180
So I'd just urge you
to be careful not

01:26:44.180 --> 01:26:48.680
to undo the current statutory
construction if you start thinking

01:26:48.680 --> 01:26:53.970
about ways to address so-called
not core copyright issues.

01:26:53.970 --> 01:26:55.270
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: OK.

01:26:55.270 --> 01:26:56.570
Thank you.

