01:27:31.630 --> 01:27:34.370
But actually, there's a tremendous
amount of commerce which is enabled

01:27:34.370 --> 01:27:39.800
by fair use and hacking T
forever, bypassing TPMs, yeah.

01:27:39.800 --> 01:27:41.100
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

01:27:41.100 --> 01:27:42.400
Mr. Turnbull?

01:27:42.400 --> 01:27:43.700
&gt;&gt; Bruce H. Turnbull: Yeah,
I just wanted to say quickly

01:27:43.700 --> 01:27:49.150
that as the representative of
two of the TPMs in wide use,

01:27:49.150 --> 01:27:52.680
our interests-- and I think the
Copyright Office has taken those

01:27:52.680 --> 01:27:55.110
into account under
this other factor--

01:27:55.110 --> 01:27:59.200
have to do with the integrity
of our licensing system,

01:27:59.200 --> 01:28:01.920
which is not necessarily copyright,

01:28:01.920 --> 01:28:05.780
whether the particular thing
is a copyright infringement

01:28:05.780 --> 01:28:08.270
or fair use or whatever it is.

01:28:08.270 --> 01:28:12.590 position:56%
It has to do with whether the
overall system can continue to exist

01:28:12.590 --> 01:28:17.170
and the benefits from that
are to the copyright system

01:28:17.170 --> 01:28:19.310
and the user-- using
public as a whole.

01:28:19.310 --> 01:28:25.710 position:56%
And so, as a more generic point, I'd
say that as you address the things

01:28:25.710 --> 01:28:29.260
which are sometimes
called not core copyright,

01:28:29.260 --> 01:28:32.760
you need to be really
careful because, again,

01:28:32.760 --> 01:28:36.820
sort of eliminating other factors
would potentially eliminate things

01:28:36.820 --> 01:28:39.300
that we think are important
for you to consider

01:28:39.300 --> 01:28:43.960
in the context of expressive works.

01:28:43.960 --> 01:28:45.260
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

